A series of explosions in Thai resorts killed four people.
Several explosions occurred in southern Thailand on Friday morning.
As a result of the attack, four people died, 19 were wounded.
The epicenter of the explosions came to the city of Hua-Hin.
Among the victims were ten foreigners, citizens of four states, and no Russians among them.
None of the terrorist groups have taken responsibility for the incident yet, but the country’s internal ministry has rushed to say that Islamists are not involved in the incident.
Some people are suspected of organizing the explosions.
According to local police preliminary data, the scale and characteristics of the explosions indicate that they were directed against the country-leading military.
Attacks occurred on popular tourist resorts, including the Patong Beach in Phuket area and the cities of Hua-Hin, Trang and Surat-Tani.
After the arrival of the military junta to power in the country in 2014, economic growth fell from 7.2% (2012) to 2.8% (2015), but tourism remained one of the few industries that demonstrated development.
In 2016, the country has already visited 14 million people, which is 1.5 million more than in 2015.
The first suspects in the preparation and organization of the attacks have already been arrested, police colonel Krisana Patanacharoen said.
It’s too early to talk about the targets, he added, but the country’s foreign ministry is “confident that they are not linked to international extremist groups.”
“It’s too early to make conclusions,” Mr. Patanacharoen said.
But we know exactly that these incidents are not directly related to any kind of terrorism, they are actually local divergences, and we are trying to identify the personalities of those who stood behind them.
The explosion took place on the birthday of Queen Secret of Thailand.
The Thai junta considers the protection of the monarchy as one of its main priorities, so the incident is most likely to be directed against it.
According to the statement of police general Sithicya Shrisopacharoenrat, the bombs were exploded remotely with a half-hour difference.
They were hidden inside trees on the lively streets filled with lunch in restaurants by tourists.
One of the four killed was a Thai girl who traded street food.
The identity of the victims is unknown, but it is known that they are residents of four foreign states.
According to the Royal Police of Thailand, among them four citizens of Germany, three subjects of the Netherlands, two citizens of Italy and an Austrian citizen.
There are no Russians among the victims of the explosions, the press service Rosturism.
Local experts also link the explosions to the August 7 referendum, on which 61.4% of the country’s population supported the draft new constitution.
It was prepared by a constitutional commission appointed by the military junta.
The voters had to determine whether they support a system in which the Supreme House of Parliament is fully appointed by the military and has a significant role in the election of the country’s Prime Minister.
The new system has been adopted and will be tested for the first time in the 2017 parliamentary elections.
On May 22, 2014, a military coup took place in Thailand under the leadership of the country's army commander Prayut Chang-Och.
To this step, he said, the army was pushed by the continuing political crisis and the lack of progress in negotiations between the government and the opposition.
The military established the National Council of Peace and Order, introduced the Command Hour and Censorship, dismantled the protesters and the Supreme Chamber of Parliament.
Bangkok is in emergency
The Thai government, led by Prime Minister Yinglak Chinavat, in January 2014 announced an emergency state in Bangkok and neighboring provinces.
The special regime lasted 60 days.
Two explosions occurred in Bangkok.
In January 2014, two explosions occurred at the Victory Monument in the centre of Bangkok, where one of the main protests took place, in which 28 people were injured, five of them in critical condition.
Explosions occurred by unknown people on motorcycles.
The authorities have strengthened security measures in the capital and attracted military forces to protect the protesters.
