Former Chairman of the FSI was sentenced to court
The Prosecutor's Office of Moscow has approved the accusation on the investigated Criminal case of theft of budget funds allocated to the needs of the FSIN of Russia.
For the court, the former head of the prison department Alexander Raymer and his deputy who caused FSIN damages in the amount of more than 2.7 billion rubles.
The capital prosecutor's office sent a criminal case against former director of the FSIN of Russia Alexander Raymer, his former deputy Nikolai Krivolapov, as well as the director of the FGUP "Center of Information and Technical Supply and Communications of the Federal Service of Punishment" (FGUP CITOS) Viktor Opridelov.
Depending on the role and degree of participation in the committing of crimes, they are accused by the RSU of Moscow under section 3 of article 285 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of official powers, causing severe consequences), section 4 of article 159 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (fraud, committed using its official status, in the composition of an organized group, in a large scale).
Furthermore, Krivolapov is accused by Article 222 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (Illegal acquisition and storage of ammunition).
According to the version of the SCR, in 2010-2012, these persons fraudulently kidnapped from the state treasury the budget funds allocated to the FSIN to provide the department with electronic monitoring systems of controlled persons, so-called electronic bracelets.
In order to steal budget money, the participants of the group developed a scheme according to which the under-control company FGUP CITOS, with which the relevant state contracts were concluded, produced technical means of control and supervision, including "electronic bracelets", and implemented at prices exceeding several times.
Despite the fact that the FGUP CITOS did not have production equipment, buildings, facilities for placing production capacities, allowing to create a finished production cycle of "electronic bracelets", five state contracts were concluded between him and the FSIN of Russia for the amount of more than 3.3 billion rubles.
As a result of this scheme on the accounts of the Samarian branch of the FGUP was more than 2 billion rubles, of which 1.2 billion rubles were stolen.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles of funds received personally by Mr. Raymer in his office from one of the participants, the criminal case against which was assigned to a separate proceedings.
Nikolai Krivolapov, who was involved in the machinery, was found unknown origin of the gun to the reward pistol, which allowed him to submit additional charges.
In the case, the volume of which amounted to 133 volumes, the FSIN to the accused claimed compensation of material damage in the amount of 2.7 billion rubles.
Footballer Hakan Shukura is suspected of being involved in the coup.
The Turkish authorities issued an order for the arrest of the former footballer, and then a member of the parliament, Hakan Shukur, and conducted surveys in two houses of his family.
The star of the Turkish football of the 1990s - early 2000s, the attacker Hakan Shukur is being sought by the country's authorities in connection with the attempt of a state coup that took place last month.
Forward, who finished his sports career in 2008, is accused of belonging to a “armed terrorist group.”
It is about the Hezmet movement, a society linked to the famous Turkish religious actor and oppositionist Fethullah Gülen.
It is his president Erdogan who considers the organizer of the attempt to a military coup that took place on July 15.
Fethullah Gülen lives in the United States, and the Turkish authorities demand his extradition.
According to local media, the arrest order was issued today, the police have already conducted surveys in two houses belonging to the family of the former footballer.
According to the version of the investigation, the organization of Fethullah Gülen, in addition to Hakan Shukur himself, included his father.
However, neither the former footballer nor his loved ones were there.
Now he and his family live in the United States.
As a footballer, Hakan Shukur defended the colors of several Turkish clubs and played for the country's team.
He spent much of his career in Galatasaray.
The list of foreign clubs includes Italian "Torino", "Inter" and "Palermo", as well as English "Blackburn".
He did not spend more than one season in any of them.
Hakan Shukur remains the most successful attacker of the Turkish team: in his asset 112 matches for the national team and 51 balls.
In 2013, Hakan Shukur left his parliamentary position due to a corrupt investigation around Erdogan’s party and its nearby surroundings.
According to the Turkish newspaper Hurriyet, at least 42 journalists were arrested on July 25 in Turkey.
They are accused of contributing to a military coup and connections with the opposition Islamic prophet Fethullah Gülen, who lives in the United States.
Given the severity of the accusations, media officials can wait for prolonged prison periods - from ten years to several lifetime prisons.
