The Russian Copper Company (RMK) is ready to take on social responsibility and pay more attention to the environmental aspects of its business.
This is confirmed, for example, by the fact that the RMK took for the modernization of one of the oldest and environmentally “dirty” enterprises in the country – the Karabash Medeplavil Combinate.
The Karabash Medeplavil Factory was founded by the British shareholders under the leadership of Leslie Urkhart in 1910.
In Soviet times it was a significant industrial enterprise for the economy of the country, and it actually provided the vitality of the whole city.
However, in the 1990s, due to financial problems, production was stopped, causing serious social problems in Karabach.
In 1998 the decision was made to renew the work of the Karabakh Medeplavil Combinate.
It was also necessary to solve one of the main problems of the Karabakh plant - environmental.
By the beginning of the 2000s, Karabach was already sadly known as the environmental disaster zone.
The situation on Karabashmedi began to change in 2004, after the company passed under the management of the Russian copper company.
The company began to modernize production, which gradually reduced the environmental burden.
This was recently noted by the governor of the Chelyabinsk region Boris Dubrovsky, who visited Karabashmed in the first numbers of July.
The head of the Southern Ural called the great changes that have occurred with the enterprise since "Karabashmed" passed into the group of the RMK.
The main event for the modernization of Karabashmedi in recent years was the construction of a new serum-oxid plant, which allows to capture up to 99.9% of metallurgical gases.
According to the president of the Russian copper company Allowlod Levin, the volume of investments in this project amounted to about 7 billion rubles.
The next stage of the modernization of the ZOO "Karabashmed" - the reconstruction of the converter transfer.
The replacement of three converters, pipelines, and gas pipeline is planned for the end of 2017.
The cost of the project is 2.5 billion rubles.
In addition, at the end of 2016 it is planned to launch a new cleaning facility of industrial goods worth 1 billion rubles.
In turn, the amounts of taxes deposited in the budget of the city of Karabakh will also increase.
