The economy of Ethiopia is developing with an impressive pace.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly – there is even a new suburban train in the capital Addis Abeba.
And its streets are usually quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly an example of democracy – human rights organizations constantly mention government repressions – the opposition on the territory of the state was interrupted by the fact that the dissidents were actually forced to silence.
Many of them were sent, imprisoned, killed or expelled into remote deserts.
But that can change.
“If people are constantly suppressed and they do not leave them any other option than to protest, the rebellion will rise,” said Seum Teshome, a lecturer at the University in Central Ethiopia.
All the youth protests.
The generation protests.
The complaints are numerous, starting from land use, ending with the capture of power by a government coalition.
After the widely criticized elections last year, the government party and its allies have completely suppressed the opposition and now control 100% of the Parliament.
At the same time, tensions along the border with Eritrea are growing; the struggle for this uncertain, controversial border has caught hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts are afraid that separatist groups that have been more or less destroyed in recent years, such as the Oromos Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to exploit anxiety and rearmed themselves.
A number of factors explain why gorgeous feelings, for several years boiling in the depths of the soul, are burning now.
The first would seem completely harmless: smartphones.
Only in the last couple of years a large number of Ethiopians have been able to communicate on social networks, as cheap smartphones have become common, and the internet service has become better.
Even when the government closes access to Facebook and Twitter, as it often happens, especially during protests, many people still find the opportunity to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that this is how they were organized for the protests.
The second is that there is more solidarity between Orom and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oromo and Amhara are not natural allies.
Thro the centuries, Amhara from the mainly Christian mountainous regions of Ethiopia has prospered in politics and business, exploiting the Oromos, many of which are Muslims and live in low regions.
