“We’re going to act together under a single beginning,” said MULATU HEMECU, the leader of Oromos.
The major protests took place in the districts of Amhara and Orom.
Many of Amhara and Oromos feel that Etiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tiger ethnic group, which accounts for about 6 percent of the population and which controls military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third cause of anxiety is the loss of Meles Zenaway.
Meles, the former rebellion leader, served as Prime Minister of Ethiopia for 17 years, until his death from an unknown disease in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could predict danger.
Analysts claim that he skillfully recognised the first signals of dissatisfaction and used intelligence to obtain data and dismantle opponents.
“The current regime lacks good sense,” said Abdi, an analyst of conflict situations.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Heilemariam Desalyan, appeared nonewhere and took the place of Meles.
Unlike Meles, who was a native from the Tigre region in northern Ethiopia, Heilmariam is a southern man.
Analysts say he does not use the trust of the Tiger-controlled security services.
Many are afraid that this will result in even more blood flow.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such anxiety was in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what analysts said seemed to be elections that the government shut down and then falsified the results.
During the subsequent repressions many Protestants were killed, although in a smaller number compared to the last months, and this period of tensions passed relatively quickly.
Development experts expressed their gratitude to the Ethiopian leaders for the long-looking development of infrastructure, such as the new cross-city train and significant successes in the fight against poverty.
But it is obvious that this did not stop the growth of internal dissatisfaction by the government of Ethiopia.
And it takes a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondara, the city of Amhara, attacked the Tigers-owned enterprises, and anti-Tigers hatred on social networks becomes comprehensive.
Analysts say the protesters put the United States and other Western allies in uncomfortable situation.
The U.S. government has used Ethiopia as a base for drone flights over neighboring Somalia, although it has recently announced that it has closed the base.
On the one hand it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand it does not want its ally to lose power in the already unstable region.
