The latest mission of the Kepler Space Telescope helped astronomers collect the most complete catalogue of the rotating speeds of the stars belonging to the Playout.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars rotate at different speeds and how the rotation periods are related to the formation of planets.
“We hope that by comparing our results with other star collections, we will learn more about the interconnection between the mass of the star, its age and even the history of its solar system,” said Louise Riball, a scientist at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the California Institute of Technology.
The Playout is located 445 light years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the gathering now only reach maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They turn as quickly as they will never be again.
At their peak rotating speeds, these adult stars throw out large amounts of star wind.
Travelling through the magnetic fields of the stars, these winds have a braking effect on the stars.
As the star ages, its rotation speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star, tracing the time between the appearance of recognizable star spots, such as sun spots.
The latest rotating speed catalog suggests that more massive stars rotate slower than less massive stars.
Fishermen compare the stars to the dancers: the larger make the pirates slower than the smaller.
“In the Pleiad ballet, we see that those that turn slowly are usually more massive, while those that turn faster are usually very light stars,” Riball said.
Since the Playout is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory to compare the properties of the stars with the rotation speeds.
“The Pleiada Star Assembly provides a starting point for the theoretical patterns of star rotation, both younger and older,” Riball said.
We still want to learn a lot about how, where and why the stars slow down their rotation and hang their "dancing shoes" on the hole.
Ryball and colleagues have detailed their latest analysis of the Playout rotation speeds in three new articles, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
