Compressed between Angola and South Africa, Namibia was severely affected during the long struggle against apartheid.
However, after independence from South Africa in 1990, this country with a population of 2.4 million people has achieved huge successes, especially in the last few years.
The main reason for Namibia’s success is that the government is paying a lot of attention to education.
While people in developed countries perceive as free primary and secondary education, in many poor countries, secondary and even primary schools require a fee for education.
Moreover, governments are often advised to introduce training fees to “refund costs”.
However, in Namibia education in primary schools is free.
Secondary education has been free since 2015.
The authorities of the country are also actively working on other important areas.
The efforts to eradicate malaria have reduced the number of annual cases of the disease by 97% over the last ten years.
Contrary to the international trend of growing inequality, it is decreasing in Namibia.
Compared to the 1993 indicator, the Gini coefficient, which is the standard indicator of inequality in income distribution, fell by 15 points.
Then, 23 years ago, this figure was one of the highest in the world.
The poverty rate dropped from 69% in 1993 to less than 30%.
The number of people living in extreme poverty (less than $1.90 a day) also decreased, from 53% to less than 23%.
Namibia also has the highest freedom rating in Africa, according to Reporters Without Borders.
The country is significantly ahead of the United States and other wealthy countries.
In addition, the country has a favourable rating - one of the highest in Africa - in the "Corruption Perception Index", which is made up by human rights defenders from Transparency International.
Even now that raw materials prices fall, Namibia is able to maintain high growth rates.
At the same time, the debt ratio to GDP is around 25%, which is less than 1/3 of the debt level in the U.S. and most European countries.
Of course, Namibia has some problems.
The unemployment level, at least by traditional assessment methods, remains quite high – almost 28%.
And like other countries in the region, Namibia has a high HIV/AIDS rate – 17% of the population is infected.
According to the World Bank, Namibia is one of the countries with income above the average, but the authorities insist that their country is actually a developing country.
Namibia, of course, faces some difficulties that are characteristic of poorly developed economies.
The state has to develop a very large and dry country with a small population.
On the territory of the country in the deserts live isolated cattle tribes of hunting-collectors, who in any way must be integrated into the modern society, without losing their identity.
Integrating people that a quarter of a century ago were on the periphery of the world economy is not an easy task for any country.
It is even more difficult for Namibia: like any other country in the world, it is facing the consequences of climate change.
However, Namibia has not thought of leaving its hands, the country is solving the problems that are facing it.
Almost immediately after the independence, the authorities engaged in the creation of a diversified economy and a joint society.
It is remarkable that the competing political factions gathered together to work for the common good.
In fact, Namibia provides cheap medical care not only to its own citizens, but also to its neighbors.
About 15-20% of the visitors to medical facilities in the northern districts of Namibia are Angola citizens.
No one in Namibia is talking about building a wall that would separate the country from the poor and corrupt neighbors.
The Namibia people understood that the neighbors don’t choose, and therefore they decided not to conflict with them, but to cooperate – to share the water resources that lack, to participate in regional medical projects, to encourage investments and exchange students.
In addition, the government of Namibia justified that rich natural resources can easily become a curse, contributing to the enrichment of few by the expense of many.
The authorities understand that the revenue from the natural resources of Namibia needs to be invested in infrastructure and production capacity.
They also realize that it would be irresponsible not to pursue the maximum profit from the country’s sales of resources, and review investment laws and mining contracts to make sure that it is so.
Transparency is crucial for this process, so strong support by the government for freedom of speech is so important.
As the head of state Hague Geingob noted, the media often say something he doesn’t like.
But after the struggle for freedom from apartheid in South Africa, Namibia must defend the gained freedoms, the president says.
Not all the key resources of Namibia are exhausted.
Some - such as fishing - are considered to be renewable, and the government is making every effort to preserve and strengthen them.
Every year more than a million foreign tourists visit the country.
Namibia shows that even those countries that start with serious disadvantages – racism, colonial order, inequality and low levels of development – can stand on the path to general prosperity.
Its achievement deserves international recognition and imitation.
Many have heard of the "Golden Barna" - the oldest gold objects created by man (4600 - 4200 years before our era).
Per this was the strongest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavations of the Varna necropole, a fantastic number of gold artefacts was found - more than three thousand total weight of 6 kilograms.
Only from one cemetery, known as the "Majila No. 43", 990 gold objects with a total weight of more than 1.5 kg were extracted.
However, the official status of the world’s oldest gold may soon pass to the invisible bull found by archaeologists in July of this year.
