The busin is a golden strip swallowed into the ring.
Yavour Boyajiev, the head of the excavations in Telle Junacet, dated the discovery 4600 years before our era and said it was older than the gold of Varna for at least 200 years.
The treasures of Varna, let’s remember, date about the same period, 4600-4200 BC.
Technologies that allow perfect accuracy to date the metal do not exist.
How do you know which gold is more ancient?
Obviously, Professor Boyajiev knows more than he told Reuters: "I am completely confident that the Yunaciti gold is older than the Varna gold."
It’s a finding of extraordinary importance: it looks like it’s a small object, but it’s large enough to occupy a suitable place in history.
In an interview with Reuters Boyajiev said that in the near future scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as re- and more thoroughly explore the archaeological layer where the gold artefacts were found.
This will help to date the busin with the most accuracy possible.
The location also explains a lot.
Tel Yunaciets is a famous settlement, even if you’ve never heard of it.
Today, Tel Aviv is considered the oldest “city” in Europe.
Tel was founded by descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7th millennium BC.
Thro the subsequent centuries, the processing of metals was rapidly developed in this region, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry.
In the domestic historiography for this archaeological community there is a special name: the Balkan-Carpatic metallurgical province.
In the 5th millennium BC around the metal processing centers began to arise urban-type settlements.
Now they are called the oldest cities in Europe.
These are the most ancient of the Tel Yunacite, since the artifacts were found here from the year 4900 BC.
I would call the Tel Yunaciti a prototype of a modern city, although it is a very ancient settlement, even compared to Mesopotamia.
"This place is a thousand years older than Shumer," Boyajiev says, having regard to the commonly accepted opinion that the urban culture was born in the south of Mesopotamia - the modern Iraq.
There emerged the first cities in the usual sense of this word.
The excavation of the Yunaciti body has been carried out since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists excavated 12 hectares, which is about a third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
The remains of the fortress wall, which once reached three meters in height, were found.
From houses and workshops little has been preserved, but archaeologists clearly distinguish streets, public buildings, urban density, "business center" and residential areas.
Tel Yunacians are often referred to as the "bird city": there were found dozens of glinated bird figures.
All birds are depicted in a state of rest, from which the assumption arose that they were not decorative objects, but an object of local cult.
The bird city was destroyed about 4100 years before our era – possibly by the Indo-European tribes coming from the northeast.
There were no cities, but there were horses and weapons.
The three-meter fortress walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists discovered obvious signs of a brutal battle: inside the houses were found remains of elderly, women and children with traces of wounds caused by the battle towers.
New findings and new facts appear every year, changing usual ideas about the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the "lost" first civilization of Europe, born on the Balkans.
